 for this characterization. Provocative and persuasive at turns, this collection of essays provides a bold and innovative reinterpretation of the Supreme Court after the Civil War.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 7aLAW / General.2bisacsh  ajustice, judicial system, judges, law, lawyers, politics, political, politicians, government, governing, power, supreme court, reconstruction period, 19th century, united states of america, american history, historical studies, civil war, usa, slavery, slaves, freedom, freedmen, free, democracy, democratic, national, nation, country, politically mobilized, debate, discussion, equal rights, amendments, changes, decisions, read mission, policymakers.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package Archive 1960-1989z978311066784440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226465432423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226465432/original  a978-3-11-066784-4  University of Chicago Press eBook Package Archive 1960-1989c1960d1989  aGBV-deGruyter-alles